                {
                  q: 'What is the difference between mutually exclusive events and independent events?',
                  a: 'Mutually exclusive: A and B cannot both occur — P(A∩B) = 0. If A happens, B is impossible. Example: a single coin flip cannot be both heads and tails. Independent: knowing A occurred gives no information about B — P(A∩B) = P(A)·P(B). Example: two separate coin flips. Crucially, mutually exclusive events with P(A)>0 and P(B)>0 are NEVER independent — if A occurs, B definitely did not (P(B|A)=0 ≠ P(B)). In ML, feature independence (as assumed by Naive Bayes) means conditional independence: P(xᵢ,xⱼ|y) = P(xᵢ|y)·P(xⱼ|y), not marginal independence.',
