                  a: 'A logistic regression models P(y=1|x) = σ(wᵀx) = p. If we assume y ~ Bernoulli(p), the likelihood of observing a single example is p^y·(1−p)^(1−y). The log-likelihood is y·log(p) + (1−y)·log(1−p). Summing over n examples and negating gives the binary cross-entropy loss: L = −Σ[yᵢlog(pᵢ) + (1−yᵢ)log(1−pᵢ)]. Minimising cross-entropy = maximising the Bernoulli log-likelihood = MLE. This is why logistic regression is called a discriminative generative model.',
