            detail: {
              overview: `CUPED: Controlled-experiment Using Pre-Experiment Data (Deng et al., 2013, Microsoft Research)

Core idea: remove the pre-experiment variability from the outcome metric to reduce noise.

CUPED estimator:
  Ȳ_cuped = Ȳ − θ · (X̄ − E[X])
  θ = Cov(Y, X) / Var(X)   (regression coefficient of Y on pre-experiment covariate X)

Variance reduction:
  Var(Ȳ_cuped) = Var(Ȳ) · (1 − ρ²)
  where ρ = Cor(Y, X)  (correlation between post and pre-experiment metric)

What it achieves:
  ρ = 0.5 → variance reduced by 25%
  ρ = 0.7 → variance reduced by 51%
  ρ = 0.8 → variance reduced by 36%  ← note: ρ=0.8 → 1-0.64=36%
  ρ = 0.9 → variance reduced by 81%  ← 90% day-to-day user correlation

Equivalent to: regression-adjusted estimator
  Y_cuped = Y − θ·(X − X̄)
  This removes variation in Y that is predictable from X (pre-experiment baseline)

CUPED in practice:
  For CTR experiments: X = user CTR in the 7 days before experiment start
  For revenue: X = user revenue in prior period
  For model evaluation: X = per-sample score from previous model version
  Requires: pre-experiment data covering the same users`,
